sentences: In 1947, he recorded with Charlie Parker.

He was the guitarist on the album Julie Is Her Name (1955) by Julie London, which includes the standard "Cry Me a River", selling a million copies and demonstrated Kessel's chordal approach to guitar.
During the 1960s, Kessel worked for Columbia Pictures and was a member of a band of sessions musicians known as The Wrecking Crew.
Kessel was rated the No. 1 guitarist in Esquire, DownBeat, and Playboy magazine polls between 1947 and 1960.
From 1961 to 1974, Gibson Guitars manufactured Barney Kessel artist signature guitars in Standard and Custom models.
Kessel was in poor health after suffering a stroke in 1992.
He died from a brain tumor at his home in San Diego, California, on May 6, 2004, at the age of 80.

sentences: Barney Kessel (October 17, 1923 – May 6, 2004) was an American jazz guitarist born in Muskogee, Oklahoma.
The band members nicknamed him "Fruitcake" because he practiced up to 16 hours a day.
During the day, he worked as a studio musician and at night played jazz in clubs.

At one point, after a two and a half hour session to record a one-chord song, "The Beat Goes On," Kessel is reported to have stood up and proclaimed, "Never have so many played so little for so much."
He was then married to Betty Jane (BJ) Baker for 16 years.
His 3rd wife Joanne (Jo) Kessel lasted 10 years, and he was married to his 4th wife, Phyllis Kessel, for 12 years.
